      "writtenOn": "2020-07-09T19:06:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This doesn\u0027t feel quite right to me -- we can\u0027t ever directly map a generic buffer, but only if it\u0027s a subclassed transfer buffer? It feels like it should be the other way around, or handled in here somehow. And IIRC the plan was to move away from specialized buffer types.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 56,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 56,
        "endChar": 41
      },
      "revId": "2c0fa8d6b82fcc5833bfdae0209d17b79588e2d5",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f825b4de_efc2e962",
        "filename": "src/gpu/dawn/GrDawnBuffer.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 56,
      "author": {
        "id": 5036
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-09T19:26:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah I\u0027m really not a big fan of the separate class at all, but dawn is very explicit that only our transfer buffers (to and from gpu) are directly mappable. All others have to be GPU only.\n\nI at first did have it all in one class, but once I started need to track whether the buffer was non mapped, map called but not returned yet, or fully mapped it seemed like a lot for generic buffer class to be managing.\n\nSome possible thoughts. If we don\u0027t mind the separate classes I do think structurally it makes sense to have a GrDawnBuffer base class then have a GrDawnTransferBuffer subclass and GrDawnGpuBuffer subclass. Each of those basically override the map call and all else is basically shared in GrDawnBuffer.\n\nOption 2 is to just put all the mapped tracking and related functions in the base class and just deal with it.\n\nOption 3 is to remove all the mapped tracking from GrDawnBuffer. Instead do something where the busy list doesn\u0027t hold GrDawnBuffers but a struct of {sk_sp\u003cGrDawnBuffer\u003e, MappedState}. Then we\u0027d have to plumb that struct into the async map calls so it knows which MappedState to update in the callback.\n\nAs much as I like the idea of merging buffers together I kind of think option 1 is the cleanest. The way Dawn itself is structured it is really begging to treat those two types of buffers differently.",
      "parentUuid": "87e16a55_9032d297",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 56,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 56,
        "endChar": 41
      },
      "revId": "2c0fa8d6b82fcc5833bfdae0209d17b79588e2d5",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
